> Kirk
>
> Minicircuits make good transformers and I have bought many small
> circuits including transformers over the years from them, but
> transformers are not antennas.  We have got the message that you are
> not interested in details, which makes you a bad source of information
> on subjects you don't understand :)
>
> By far the most widespread use of ferrite rod antennas is in
> medium-wave (and in Europe long-wave) portable radios.  Let's have a
> look at the simple RF system calculation for a portable radio,
> assuming a 1 MHz carrier and a bandwidth of 10 kHz for the AM audio
> transmission.
>
> The thermal noise floor kTB for a 10 kHz bandwidth, as we have already
> seen, is -134 dBm.  Assuming a noise figure of 5 dB for the receiver,
> and a 30-dB signal to noise ratio, we arrive at the signal power
> required from the antenna, and it is -134 + 30 + 5 dBm, in other words
> -99 dBm.
>
> A minimum field-strength of 1 mV/m can be assumed for an AM
> transmission, which means a power density of 2.654 nW per square
> metre, or -56 dBm per square metre.  We also know that the capture
> area for a lossless small antenna at 1 MHz, from the much-quoted
> formula, is 10729 square metres, or +40 dBsm.  Therefore the power
> delivered by a lossless antenna is -56+40 dBm, in other words -16 dBm.
>
> So we have -16 dBm delivered by a lossless antenna, but for our radio
> we only need -99 dBm to meet the system requirement.  That is a margin
> of 83 dB and it explains why ferrite antennas enjoys such popularity
> in portable radios, because 83 dB is a typical radiation efficiency
> (in other words signal power loss) for this type of antenna.
>
> It also explains why ferrite rod antennas are the size they are, in
> other words why they are not made one tenth the size, for example,
> even though that would make the unit manufacturing costs much less.
> You can be sure that the Japanese and Chinese manufacturers of
> portable radios are familiar with these numbers, even though they
> might not have reached New Jersey yet . . :).
>
> If anyone can see anything wrong with these figures, please say so,
> they need checking  :)
>
> Why is the radiation efficiency so low for these antennas? it's
> because of the minuscule radiation resistance compared to the loss
> resistance, which Alan P. and I seem to agree about in an approximate
> kind of way.  But you need to get into the details to appreciate this
> side of the discussion.
>
> It also explains why Kirk is shy about details :)
>
> Alan G3NOQ
